    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "2a7b48892913c5a7",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "2a7b48892913c5a7",
        "text": "Forms are considered complete in system theory only if it is also determined what they have to exclude and at the same time keep available so that they can make a difference. In the case of illegal/legal, this negative condition (the zero of the medium) could be lawlessness: as soon as lawlessness prevails, the distinction legal/illegal makes no difference and therefore lawlessness must be excluded and at the same time available as a negative contrast foil, i.e. re-enclosed. The latter is done in two ways: Legality threatens with lawlessness and thereby legitimizes itself - and illegality flirts with lawlessness and thereby motivates."
      },
      "date": 1655890721169
    },
